segments.text: All right, today is December the 1st, and I'm interviewing Dr. Barbara Stone, associate professor of interdisciplinary education, who was appointed to Texas A&M, or came to Texas A&M in 1977, and has worked in the IDED department.
And we're going to talk a little bit about some of the changes that you have perceived, Dr. Stone, since you arrived at A&M.
things that have occurred that you feel had great impact on the College of Education and how you have seen the changes and what has happened since you have been here?
Could you just think back to the major things that have changed since you've arrived?
Well, of course, the change in the dean was dramatic change.
changing in some of the departments, the decline of IVTE, or industrial ed, the switching of ed tech from industrial ed to IDED.
There are a number of things of that nature.
Can you give me a little background?
What brought about these changes?
You know, an idea?
Yep.
Do you want to talk about it?
Sure.
Why not?
OK.
I can't remember exactly how long ago it was, but it might have been 81 or 82.
Cargan suggested that he did more than suggest.
He caused a planning committee to be formed to a representative from Ag Ed, Industrial Ed,
voc ed and adult ed, the gang of four, to look into the possibility of combining IDED and IED into one department.
At the onset of that, it was my understanding that the dean said that neither of the existing chairmen would
be the chair of the new department.
At that point, also, voc ed was a part of IDED.
That may or may not have come out in some other interview.
As a matter of fact, IDED was started initially because there was federal money for voc ed fellows, doctoral fellows.
I think there were 16 of them.
And they needed somewhere to put them.
and their whatever it was, so they made IDED, which is not a department.
It is an administrative bucket.
At that point, Adult Ed was in Ed-Ed, and I do not know how Adult Ed got from Ed-Ed to IDED, but it happened before 77 before I came.
I didn't even know that.
In any case,
We struggled, the gang of four struggled for some year with numerous meetings and going back and reporting to our constituencies and so forth.
And each time the adult ed faculty declined to join industrial ed or to join a total group because we felt that adult ed was far more than just industrial training for adults.
And we
got away with not going along.
There have been some consequences, in my personal opinion, that went along with our refusal to play.
But the upshot of that, I think, although I'm oversimplifying it, I'm sure, is that the Voc Ed program has been virtually destroyed.
And that's too bad, because it was a viable program and it serves a need.
I think now they're making an effort to bring it back again now that the leadership of IDT has changed.
But there are a number of things of that nature that we've experienced.
I don't know if this makes any sense out of context.
Well, it's a first.
No, that's fine.
In other words, the fact that they could not be joined with
IDED or voc ed, is that what really had the most impact on it, sort of dissimulating?
On voc ed?
No.
Well, you would need to verify this with a voc ed perception if you didn't care to.
But from my, I honestly believe it was an in-house fight that some of the faculty in industrial ed felt that they knew all about voc ed.
And the voc ed people are joint split appointments.
And so there was a power fight, and they lost.
Now, that's oversimplified and what have you, but it's what I think happened.
The political influence.
And you asked what I thought.
That's what it is.
OK, here we go.
So that kind of covers what you feel has caused the major changes.
What about just within IDED?
Is there something, some other changes that have occurred since you arrived in 77 in the last two years?
Oh, yeah, when I first came,
IDED, because it's a non-department, anybody can teach a course in IDED.
And the credits for the teacher go back to the teacher's department so that we don't own IDED.
Oh, I see.
It's an administrative device, but McNamara can teach something and did for a while.
Don Clark can teach something and IDED doesn't get those credits in terms of budget and what have you.
They go back to Clark's own department or Grace Chisholm or what have you.
But originally when I came there were I guess as many as 15 faculty members who considered themselves IDED faculty members.
Ag Ed people, Voc Ed people were in there.
industrial ed people and stuff.
And so when we had a meeting of IDED to talk about curriculum or admissions requirements or something, the whole world was telling adult ed what we had to do.
And we had endless meetings that had to be sat through to be believed.
That got peeled away.
And I have now, well, voc ed's
was taken and put into, or they agreed to go into industrial ed.
We kind of knocked away the ag ed a little bit, but still a couple of the ag ed, one of the ag ed faculty members will chair an adult ed committee from time to time, Jim Christiansen.
And we consider him really an adult ed person.
Has Don Seaman been the IDED director, I mean, chair the whole time since it's been in existence?
No.
Don Clark was its initial den mother.
Okay.
When he was associate dean of the College of Education for research.
Oh, he held both?
He was both.
And, in fact, it was Don Clark who hired me in May of 77, or April or whatever it was.
By the time I got here in August, I went to Don Clark and I said, hi.
And he said, I'm not your boss.
And I said, wonderful, who is?
And so he sent me to some chap who was then coordinator of the vocab program, who had become chair, not chair, coordinator of IDE.
I can't even remember his name.
He left.
And I went and I said, hello.
And he said, I'm not your boss.
Oh.
So then I ended up with Don Seaman, you know, saying, look, somebody's going to call us coordinator.
Because it's not a department.
So that, he kind of evolved into that position.
Well, he got a, well, no, there's a story that goes with that, too.
When this Vulcan person left, whatever his name was,
There was still voc-ed faculty and adult-ed faculty, plus these appendage faculty members.
And we got called into a meeting in the little conference room on the seventh floor with Dean Hubert.
And Dean Hubert spent a half an hour telling us why he had selected Don Seaman as the coordinator of that meeting.
See, I hadn't gotten all of that story yet.
And, well, I had only interviewed one in this department, so I needed all that background to tie it all together.
Because that department is hard.
And everybody, in fact, Dean Corrigan said that to me the other day, you know, by talking to Huber, about how did this all happen?
How did you get this department, you know, started?
Or, you know, how did it come about?
And he said it was because of the need for that right, a grant, and didn't know it.
And also, well...
I'll tell you some more pieces not on tape.
Okay.
All right.
Now, do you feel that the college is achieving its mission of teaching, research, and service, the mission of the land grant colleges?
And I guess to what extent, I mean, do you feel?
Because there's been some changes with emphasis, you know, some departments emphasizing one more than the other or feeling that they're doing more.
research or teaching or service or whatever.

Well, it's my understanding that Caravan feels, and furthermore, it's my understanding that the administration of the university feel that faculty members can negotiate to emphasize the right to emphasize any one of the three in any given year.
They've made that, I think, very clear in the Tenure and Promotion Advisory Committee of the college.
How do you balance yourself?
Me?
I heavily emphasize teaching.
Second is research.
Second is service.
And third is research.
In your department, is that the norm, pretty much?
Or does it vary within the department of people also?
It varies with individuals.
But because we teach off campus, and we have such a heavy load of graduate students,
None of us are very heavily into research, because we choose to work with the students first.
And time and energy goes.
And there are five of us and 100 doctoral students.
And it's wonderful.
We have the best student group in the world, without any question.
But there isn't.
Well, I suppose there would be time if one wanted to spend all one's time doing that.
When you teach, I taught in Corpus this semester, and that's six weekends gone.
And then you come back and you do all week two, and I'm not complaining.
No.
But I'm just saying that I choose to work with students rather than to do research at this point.
But you do not get pressure, and you also don't get penalized if you don't.
I don't think we get promoted like other people.
I don't think we will get promoted like other people when it reaches the university level.
I don't care what they say.
You mean anybody that is not working heavy on research?
Sheila, could you get that and get a number, please?
That's just my .
Let me say another thing about that.
I think more than research, I believe that getting funded projects gets you promoted.
And that takes more time yet, and also takes time away from the students.
I don't honestly see how one can do all of those things and do them all well.
And I know they say you can choose, but I don't believe that they mean it when it comes to promotion time.
Has that always been the case, or is it changing gradually as far as emphasis?
I don't know.
OK.
Under Dean Hubert and Dean Corrigan, have you perceived a difference in the emphasis?
Much more emphasis now on getting funded projects for which you get no release time, for which you get no space to put your project people.
Linda has umpteen projects working out of what used to be our conference room, which got taken away from us without anybody even saying anything to us.
You've got all that story.
Right.
So that it's a difficult kind of thing, and I understand that they are working under pressure from other people as well.
the dean.
It's the higher?
Sure.
OK. Now, of course, you work mostly with graduate students.
Isn't that correct, in the department?
Yes.
I occasionally work with one undergraduate course in volunteer administration.
Because the tremendous growth at Texas A&M would not probably affect your work with students as much as it would the undergraduate faculty, or has it?
Because 100 students for five faculty
For doctoral students, as you almost have seen, and on the one hand, we get told to reduce the number, and on the other hand, we get told to be sure the count's up.
How are you going to do that?
No, I think the College of Education probably has been impacted least by the growth of the university.
Because we've always had more graduate, or for a number of years, we've had more graduates than undergraduates anyway.
Or about 50-50.
Because there's Ed Ed and there's us, and we only deal with graduate students.
And also Ed Psych?
Ed Psych has some undergraduate, not a major, but some undergraduate courses.
Some undergraduate courses.
There's service courses, special ed and some other things.
Right.
Okay.
What about collaboration among the departments within the college and then even with the college and other colleges outside?
Have you perceived any changes in that?
Really, I think the collaboration is good.
When Paulette and I became editors of one of our national journals, I had to learn a number of things about computer applets and that sort of thing.
I didn't know beans about it.
And I ricocheted around that campus for about six months getting all the information and the training I needed.
And everybody was uniformly marvelous and helpful and excited about the project.
I mean, the people in the computing service center.
The guy who's head of the philosophy department regularly uplinks computer material to Oxford University and to MIT.
And he said, this is how we do it.
Everybody was just marvelous.
So on that basis, nobody gave me the slightest hint they didn't have time or they weren't interested.
And that's almost across the university when I've had that kind of need.
But you had a unique opportunity to do it, whereas maybe other faculty members do not have that same opportunity.
Well, I don't know.
I'm also not very sophisticated as an individual.
And when I need to know something, I run around and say, do you know about this and can you help me?
And it may be they were, you know, taken aback by a foolish lady doing all that.
I don't know.
But they were very helpful.
When most of the contacts I've had have been in the Senate and the Graduate Council and in doctoral committees and working with graduate council reps. Have you been on the Senate?
You said on the back of the Senate?
Yes.
And I'm now on the Graduate Council.
What is the Graduate Council?
It is a subgroup of the Senate which attends to issues relating to graduate study, including clearing courses to be forwarded to the system.
Is that new?
No.
Was that in existence before the Senate?
Oh, yes.
But it was then, when they reorganized the administration, it was subsumed as a subgroup of the Senate.
Prior to the Senate, I guess it was the third year of the Senate, the Senate finally won the point that the graduate dean would not automatically be the chair of the graduate council.
And poor Leo.
We made Leo so mad.
Leo Berman.
Is he not there anymore?
No, he retired.
He's a marvelous person.
Now, is there another?
Is there a head of the graduate?
What they did, they had a Rowan Scope study.
And Corrigan was on the committee, and a bunch of others.
And Sam Black, who was the Speaker of the Senate, and some other people I kind of remember.
And they basically
looked at what the graduate college was doing and came up with a suggestion that it would be done away with.
What they recommended was to put the function, most of the functions, of the graduate college in each dean's office and let each college look after itself.
And that was, I think, to have, as I understand it, to have been the procedure.
However,
Each dean then asked for an associate dean with support staff to take on those responsibilities.
And so instead of a graduate college, we have an office of graduate studies, which is presently under Dwayne Anderson, who is the associate provost for research and graduate study.
So it didn't work with the deans individually then, doing it?
No.
Well, where was the money going to come from?
Well, and then you'd have had seven.
But in any case, Dwayne Anderson is a member ex officio, I think with vote, maybe ex officio without vote, on the Graduate Council.
Why would I be able to get all of this to triangulate and get all of the facts and figures and the times and how the policy changes?
Would the faculty senate have minutes or get information that will
What do you think of that?
I'm not sure that I need it.
But that would be differently involved in your study.
So it shouldn't be.
I think Sam Black, who is acting dean of the medical college, Sam was speaker of the Senate when this began to happen.
And he's a very friendly, articulate person.
I think Linda said there are some either minutes or agendas of the faculty.
Oh, yes, there are legal minutes.
And will those be in the archives?
I don't know.
Okay.
Talk to Patty Steele.
I want to say Steele.
I think that's right.
Patty Steele, there is an office for the faculty senate in Goodwin, on the second floor of Goodwin.
And Patty is a very nice person.
OK, great.
OK, now your department itself, IDED, how do you see that department collaborating within the college with any other departments?
Not just like, OK, you have this project on the Lifelong Learning Journal, but what are some other opportunities that faculty members in your department have to interact or to work?
or collaborate?
I know on graduate committees you all sit on the level.
We have all at one time or another participated in the inquiry groups.
The inquiry groups seem to be somewhat dormant at the moment, as far as I can tell, mostly.
But we've all worked hard at one time or another, not in the past year or so.
And we also, well,
Again, I need to know about meta-analysis.
And Dick Wilson in EdSight teaches a course in that.
So I went to him and I said, oh, other thing.
And he gave me a quick and dirty session, which was far from sufficient.
So I'm going to sit in on his course this fall, this spring.
We do things like that a lot, because we are running to keep up and learning with our students.
That's true.
OK. Now, what about perceptions of others or outsiders towards the College of Education?
Do you pick up too much of that, not only on a state level, but on a national level?
And you're involved in a lot of national type.
I'm involved, oddly, on the national level, like as a consultant to the National Forage Council.
How do you feel the College of Education at A&M is perceived as you travel around and participate in so many other things?
What do you feel?
Nothing negative.
Nobody says, oh, you're from education.
People just sort of listen to what you say.
And if it fits, they go on from there.
And if it doesn't, they say, hmm.
I've not felt any negative kind of things.
What about the reputation?
Does the reputation extend beyond the state very much of the college because of the fact that it has, you know, it produces the most teachers in the state?
Or, you know, is that known?
Are those facts known much?
I don't know.
I don't know.
So, but it's sort of... We are, as a program in our national association,
Because right now, we have probably more students making presentations at the national meetings than anybody else.
We had eight, 10 or 12 people making presentations in Washington.
IDED people?
Adult ed people.
I was a proud den mother.
I was running around, busting my buttons.
Eight presentations?
I think it was more like 12 to 15.
They're just superior people.
They really are.
That's wonderful.
One guy came up who graduated in 78, all spit and polish, with a full bird colonel, with a chest full of ribbons.
He's now in the Surgeon General's office, head of training for medical personnel for the Army.
So these were not people that are still at A&M.
They're people that have gone out and now are doing?
Well, no.
That 12 to 15 was current students, or people who just graduated.
But if we just can get the Coast Guard and the Marines, we'll have the training of all the military services tied up.
That's incredible.
That's great.
Irrelevant to your study.
No, but everything is relevant in different ways.
Now, the future and visions and what you think is going to happen to this college in the 21st century with all of the monumental changes and upheavals that are in the...
Do you have any feel for what's...
I know what I wish could happen.
What is that?

That we could somehow get ourselves together as a non-political group, which is not likely, and look at what the children need and redesign it so that the people would be ready to help the children learn it or help the adult learners learn it.
I think we're, of course I would think this, but I think we're doing a more adequate job of preparation than we are with adults than we are with children.
And that's an and all the people working with adults are doing a better job than getting.
What do you attribute that to?
Locked in ways of thinking.
On the other side?
On the other side of it.
Is it the pedagogy versus... That's too simple, really.
Yeah, but that's...

But it's, you know, if the focus is on the content and the focus on the learning plan and the focus on the textbook and the focus on third grade material, whatever in the world that is, instead of the focus on the learner and where the learner is and where the learner needs to go, that's the basic difference that I see.
And in adult ed,
What you're saying is that you tend to focus on the learner.
We have to, because there are so many different places.
And therefore, it's totally right.
Does that make sense?
Well, it makes sense to me.
And it really is the way we used to do it, historically, in colonial era.
A kid came to your school, or a teacher came through the mountains of West Virginia, and he stayed with the family, and he taught everybody as far as he could from where they were.
And then he moved on to the next valley and did the same thing.
So the focus was on the children and the learning and not on the holy content.
It's just a matter of emphasis somehow to me.
It's oversimplified, but it's a thing that really worries me.
Now, the changes, of course, that are impending are not going to have as much effect, again, on your programs or your department.
Because it's not going to change adult.
Not unless the state gets into certification of ABE teachers.
If the state gets into that certification, then our whole game will have to change it.
Certification of adult?
Adult basic ed teachers.
Is that a possibility?
I've been hearing noises about that for 11 years.
How do you feel about it?
I don't know.
It wouldn't hurt to have some way of assuring that people who teach basic education to adults are going to treat them like adults.
There's one famous story of a teacher here in San Antonio who taught children during the day and taught English to Mexican-American men at night, or Mexican men at night.
And it came Thanksgiving, and she had her daytime kids coloring turkeys, so she asked them in to color turkeys, and nobody came back the next week.
That's a true story.
It's a sad story.

So that I don't think it's really bad to have somebody, some way of assuring that the people are going to just change from looking at the content entirely to looking at the learner in relation to the content.

On the other hand, I think the literacy volunteer programs are vital and alive and growing and doing it out of love and compassion and concern and getting law-abiding training and getting whatever the other one is, LCA, I think, Literacy Council of Maryland training.
And I'd hate to kill that and bureaucratize that.
So I speak with a fork in time.
Okay.
Now, how about some highlights?
You've been there now 10 years at Texas A&M.
And I know that you have made certain contributions that you must feel good about.
You just mentioned the student, the quality of the students, and how you're seeing them perform.
And the kinds of things that they're doing has to be one of your satisfactions.
But are there any things that stand out, an insight, an anecdote, an observation that you might want to share?
That's hard.
I know.
I'm sure there's lots.
Or a highlight, maybe, of these last 10 years, other than the general student, working with the students.
It sounds trite, but every student is a highlight.
Some of them I'm joyfully getting rid of.
Some of them, I really hate to see them go.
I wrote.

My students who are trying to graduate in May, a long letter to give them all the deadlines and stuff, and ended up with something like, I'm going to put my foot in your backside and joyfully push you out of the nest onto an unsuspecting world.
